The incident offers an excellent oppor- tunity to contrast the methods of Cato and of the politica] group to which he belonged, with those of Cicero and his school. Cato wishes to punish the offenders regardless of the political consequences, or, as Cicero puts it (Aa. 2. r. 8), dicit .. . tamquam in Platonis πολιτείᾳ, nan tamquam in Romuli faece sen- tentiam.
